Book Review

‘Playing to the Edge,’ by Michael V. Hayden

By JEFF STEINFEB. 25, 2016



Continue reading the main story
Share This Page

Continue reading the main story










Photo






Gen. Michael V. Hayden sworn in before the Senate Select Intelligence Committee, May 2006.

Credit
            Jim Watson/Agence France-Presse — Getty Images        



If Michael V. Hayden were a businessman, he might be called a turnaround artist. When he was named by President George W. Bush to take over the Central Intelligence Agency in mid-2006, it was in wide disrepute. It had failed to break up the 9/11 plot. It couldn’t find Osama bin Laden. It had rubber-stamped phony intelligence about Saddam Hussein’s nonexistent weapons of mass destruction, enabling the catastrophic war in Iraq. Revelations of waterboarding and other “enhanced interrogation techniques” carried out at C.I.A. “black sites” had provoked revulsion.Even the agency’s seventh-floor executive suite reeked of malfeasance and chaos. Yellow crime-scene tape was draped across the doorway of its third-ranking official, who had been arrested on bribery charges. Other top officers had quit or were heading for the door under the fumbling, near-comical administration of Hayden’s predecessor, Porter Goss, a former Republican congressman. Adding insult to injuries, Congress had stripped the C.I.A. of its 60-year primacy among the 16 United States intelligence agencies, creating a new über-bureaucracy that would supposedly ride herd on them all.Hayden was undaunted. In 1999, he’d become head of a hidebound, creaking National Security Agency, shaved off management fat and pumped new muscle into its collection capabilities. But the nation’s premier espionage service was in many ways a harder case.“The C.I.A., deeply engaged in multiple wars, was suffering from a kind of battered child syndrome,” he writes. It needed time on the couch. And a housecleaning. “When I’d taken over N.S.A. in 1999, it needed to be shaken up. Now that I would be leading C.I.A., I knew it needed to be settled down,” he writes in a surprisingly vivid, albeit acronym-heavy, memoir that probably only a Beltway insider could truly love.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

“Playing to the Edge,” Hayden says, is his “best effort to show to the American people what their intelligence services actually do on their behalf.” But it’s really more about what C.I.A. directors spend most of their time doing, which, in Hayden’s case, amounted mostly to skirmishing with Congress, huddling with the White House and flying around the world to meet with his spy-service counterparts. Continue reading the main story







Advertisement

Continue reading the main story





During Hayden’s tenure, trekking to Capitol Hill rarely ended happily. The Democrats, in particular, were on fire over press reports of C.I.A. waterboarding, secret detention centers and the N.S.A.’s extralegal programs tracking the emails, telephone calls, web-browsing habits and financial transactions of American citizens, which he had started as its director after the 9/11 attacks.“Hearings often became shouting matches,” he recounts. “In one session I was asked if I would waterboard my daughter. Then . . . I was accused of looking bored during a lengthy lecture. . . . There were moments (a lot of them, actually) when I was convinced that several members were opposed not just to some of the agency’s actions, but to its existence.”Now a fixture on Fox News, Hayden saves special scorn for Democrats, like former Senator Jay Rockefeller, the chairman of the intelligence committee from 2007 to 2009, who he says seemed perfectly O.K. with torturing the Qaeda kingpin Khalid Shaikh Mohammed in 2003 — “I wouldn’t take anything off the table,” he told CNN at the time — but who later joined the chorus of Democrats who denounced C.I.A. methods in their censorious 2014 Senate Intelligence Committee report on torture.Why were the Democrats so hostile to the C.I.A.? They say it was because agency officials hid interrogation abuses and constantly lied to them about their effectiveness. Hayden, however, theorizes that they were offloading guilt for their own participation in the system. They should have “begun their protest in 2002 — when the trauma” of 9/11 “was recent, the threat seemed imminent and the future was in doubt,” he grouses, “not in 2014, when it was not.”“In the end,” Hayden asserts, “the Congress of the United States had no impact on the shape of the C.I.A. interrogation program going forward. Congress lacked the courage or the consensus to stop it, endorse it or amend it.” But that’s an overly narrow and legalistic interpretation of what transpired. Hayden himself admits the C.I.A. had to pull back on its most egregious interrogation methods after the outcry in Congress over abuses that were exposed by the press.“I decided that the C.I.A. program as we were recrafting it would be worth the freight and that we could buy down the tariff if we aggressively briefed Congress and solicited some public support from it,” he writes, and “if we briefed the American people in as open a way as possible; and if we quietly informed our allies more fully of the parameters and limits of what we were doing.”“For General Michael Hayden, playing to the edge means playing so close to the line that you get chalk dust on your cleats,” the Association of Former Intelligence Officers, a pro-C.I.A. group, said in a recent newsletter. Except that Hayden went well over the chalk with the N.S.A.’s warrantless data-mining programs. In a now-famous 2004 showdown with the White House, Deputy Attorney General James Comey (currently the director of the F.B.I.) threatened to resign unless the program was put on a firmer legal foundation. When the New York Times reporter James Risen got wind of the programs, Hayden took the damage-control lead, ultimately persuading the paper’s editors to sit on the story for nearly a year — until Risen forced its hand by including it in his book “State of War: The Secret History of the C.I.A. and the Bush Administration.” Hayden’s wily account of the Risen episode, as well as his views of other journalists, will probably generate media buzz. He is mostly disdainful of reporters who lust after “espionage porn” — exposing C.I.A. spying foibles, no matter the risk to national security. He sneers at Risen (“irresponsible”), others who are “hopelessly agenda-driven” (the former Times reporter Tim Weiner, The New Yorker’s Jane Mayer) and those who are “consistently anti-Bush” (like the former blogger Andrew Sullivan). Of course he has nothing but scorn for Glenn Green­wald and Laura Poitras, Boswells to the N.S.A. leaker Edward Snowden, “an incredibly naïve, hopelessly narcissistic and insufferably self-important defector.” (Nor do I escape his pique: For reporting in 2006 that the incoming House intelligence committee chairman Silvestre Reyes couldn’t tell me whether Al Qaeda was Sunni or Shia, he says I was “tough and knowledgeable, but . . . specialized in snark.”)

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Hayden is no slouch in that regard, either, taking multiple shots at Barack Obama. “More Hamlet than Patton,” he calls one of the president’s landmark speeches on combating terrorism. When Obama visits the C.I.A. and urges the assembled work force not to be “discouraged” by the administration’s release of torture memos, because “we’ve made some mistakes. That’s how we learn,” Hayden says, “the agency consensus” was that Obama “sounded a lot like Mister Rogers.” Even so, he writes, the election of the Republican senator John McCain would have been “more disruptive to the way America produced intelligence than the election of Barack Obama.”
