Hayden’s candid takes on his encounters with important foreign officials are more sober. Iraqi President Nouri al Maliki “was pretty dark.” The Kurdish leader Jalal Talabani and his advisers were “disconnected from, and somewhat cavalier about the levels of violence.” The Pakistanis “really were the ally from hell.” Bashar al-Assad is Michael Corleone’s hapless brother Fredo. His thinly disguised Israeli counterpart is “tough, tireless.”A proud product of blue-collar Pittsburgh, Hayden hints that he would have told far more stories about C.I.A. successes had agency censors let him. As it is, he dances around Israel’s role in knocking out a Syrian nuclear reactor, as well as the agency’s management of drone strikes. Amid all the killing, the spymaster remains stoic.At one point President Bush pulled Hayden aside at Camp David “for a private moment.” He asks how he’s doing “spiritually.”“Mr. President, I’m really fine,” Hayden replied, “more honestly (and firmly).”“Good, good,” the president said, and they sat down to eat.PLAYING TO THE EDGEAmerican Intelligence in the Age of TerrorBy Michael V. Hayden448 pp. Penguin Press. $30.

